%N A363082 Number of ways that n can be expressed as (j*k-1)/(j+k) with j >= k > n.
%C A363082 Numbers n such that j*k = 1+n*(j+k) always have integer solutions with j >= k > n.
%C A363082 It can be concluded that arccot(n) = arccot(j) + arccot(k).
%H A363082 Shouen Wang, <a href="https://bbs.emath.ac.cn/forum.php?mod=redirect&amp;goto=findpost&amp;ptid=15411&amp;pid=95672&amp;fromuid=46">The general term formula of an integer sequence</a>
%F A363082 As j >= k > n, let k=n+c (c is a positive integer), then j=n+(n^2+1)/c; we can easily conclude that c <= n, i.e., a(n) is the number of divisors of (n^2+1) which are not greater than n.
%F A363082 a(n) = A000005(n^2+1)/2 for n > 0.
%e A363082 For n = 7 the a(7) = 3 solutions are (17,12), (32,9), (57,8).
%e A363082 For n = 13 the a(13) = 4 solutions are (30,23), (47,18), (98,15), (183,14).
%t A363082 Table[Length@Solve[j*k == 1+n*(j + k) && j >= k > n, {j, k}, Integers], {n, 0, 99}]
%t A363082 Join[{1}, Table[Length@Divisors[n^2 + 1]/2, {n, 99}]]
